<SiteLayout site="28grams" title="Every Cooking Oil Compared" description="Every cooking oil compared: smoke point, flavor, nutrition, best uses, cost." canonical="https://28grams.vip/cooking-oils-compared" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero"><h1>Every Cooking Oil Compared</h1><p>A comprehensive guide to smoke points, flavor, and nutrition.</p></div>

    <h2>Introduction to Cooking Oils</h2>
    <p>Choosing the right cooking oil is essential for both flavor and health. Oils differ in their fat composition, smoke points, and culinary applications.</p>
    <h2>Smoke Points Explained</h2>
    <p>The smoke point is the temperature at which an oil begins to break down, producing smoke and potentially harmful compounds. High-heat cooking requires oils with high smoke points, such as avocado or refined olive oil.</p>
    <h2>Flavor Profiles</h2>
    <p>Some oils, like extra virgin olive oil and sesame oil, offer distinct flavors that can enhance a dish. Others, like canola or grapeseed oil, are neutral and won't overpower the food.</p>
    <h2>Nutrition and Health</h2>
    <p>Oils rich in monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats (like olive and avocado oil) are generally considered heart-healthy. Oils high in saturated fats (like coconut oil) should be used more sparingly.</p>
    <h2>Cost and Best Uses</h2>
    <p>While premium oils like EVOO are great for finishing dishes, less expensive neutral oils are often preferred for deep-frying or large-batch cooking.</p>
